  section
    h3 Two error models
    p Classical Ulam game:
    p $$\text{at most } e \text{ lies total}.$$
    p.fragment IMO 2012 Problem 3:
    p.fragment $$\text{no } k+1 \text{ consecutive lies}.$$
  section
    h3 IMO 2012 Problem 3
    p Alice chooses a positive integer $x$.
    p.fragment Bob asks yes/no questions.
    p.fragment Alice may lie, but not $k+1$ times in a row.
    p.fragment Bob must end with a list of at most $n$ possible values.
  section
    h3 The threshold
    p If $n\ge 2^k$, Bob can always win.
    p.fragment For large $k$, a list of size about $1.99^k$ may still be too small.
    p.reference.fragment
      a(target="_blank" href="https://www.imo-official.org/problems/IMO2012SL.pdf") IMO 2012 official shortlist

section
  section
    h3 The main proof
    p We prove why $2^k$ candidates are enough.
    p.fragment It is enough to show:
    blockquote.fragment
      | If Bob knows $x\in T$ and $|T|>2^k$,
      br
      | then Bob can eliminate one element of $T$.
  section
    h3 Why the lemma wins
    p Start with all positive integers still possible.
    p.fragment Whenever more than $2^k$ remain, eliminate one.
    p.fragment Stop when at most $2^k$ remain.
    p.fragment That final set is Bob's list.
  section
    h3 Choose candidates
    p Take $2^k+1$ candidates from $T$.
    p Call them
    p $$a,\quad 0,1,\dots,2^k-1.$$
    p.fragment Think of $0,1,\dots,2^k-1$ as all binary strings of length $k$.
  section
    h3 The special candidate
    p Bob asks:
    p.question.fragment Is $x=a$?
    p.fragment If Alice says "no" $k+1$ times in a row,
    p.fragment one of those answers must be true.
    p.fragment.red Then $x\neq a$.
  section
    h3 The other branch
    p Otherwise, Alice eventually says "yes".
    p.fragment Bob stops asking about $a$ immediately.
    p.fragment Now he asks $k$ bit questions about the other candidates.
  section
    h3 Bit questions
    p Label each other candidate by a string
    p $$b_1b_2\dots b_k\in\{0,1\}^k.$$
    p.fragment Bob asks:
    p.question.fragment Is the first bit $0$?
    p.question.fragment Is the second bit $0$?
    p.fragment $\dots$
    p.question.fragment Is the $k$th bit $0$?
  section
    h3 The missing string
    p Alice gives $k$ answers to these bit questions.
    p.fragment There is exactly one binary string $y$
    p.fragment for which all $k$ bit answers are false.
    table.bits.fragment
      tbody
        tr
          td Alice says
          td yes
          td no
          td no
          td yes
        tr
          td forced bit of $y$
          td 1
          td 0
          td 0
          td 1
  section
    h3 Why $y$ is impossible
    p Suppose $x=y$.
    p.fragment The earlier answer "yes" to $x=a$ was false.
    p.fragment The next $k$ bit answers were also false for $y$.
    p.fragment So Alice just gave $k+1$ consecutive lies.
    p.fragment.red Impossible.
  section
    h3 One number eliminated
    p Therefore $x\neq y$.
    p.fragment Bob has eliminated one candidate from $T$.
    p.fragment This proves the lemma.
  section
    h3 Coding interpretation
    p The $2^k$ strings are $k$-bit codewords.
    p.fragment Bob first forces one suspicious answer.
    p.fragment Then the $k$ bit tests make one codeword disagree with everything.
    p.fragment That would create a forbidden error block of length $k+1$.

section
  section
    h3 Why it is almost sharp
    p Why not hope for a much smaller final list?
    p.fragment Alice can spread uncertainty among many candidates.
  section
    h3 Recent inconsistency
    p For each candidate $i$, define
    p $$m_i=\text{number of consecutive recent answers inconsistent with }i.$$
    p.fragment Candidate $i$ dies only if
    p.fragment $$m_i=k+1.$$
    p.fragment Alice wants to keep every $m_i\le k$.
  section
    h3 A weight for danger
    p Choose $1.99<\lambda<2$ and set
    p $$\Phi=\sum_i \lambda^{m_i}.$$
    p.fragment Large $m_i$ means candidate $i$ is close to dying.
    p.fragment So it receives large weight.
  section
    h3 Alice's strategy
    p When Bob asks a question, Alice chooses the answer
    p that keeps $\Phi$ smaller.
    p.fragment The official proof shows:
    p.fragment if initially there are about $\lambda^k$ candidates,
    p.fragment Alice can keep $\Phi<\lambda^{k+1}$ forever.
  section
    h3 What that means
    p If some candidate reached $m_i=k+1$,
    p then its contribution alone would be $\lambda^{k+1}$.
    p.fragment But $\Phi<\lambda^{k+1}$.
    p.fragment So no candidate is ever eliminated.
    p.fragment Bob cannot force a list that small.

section
  section
    h3 The story
    table.story
      tbody
        tr.fragment
          td Ordinary Twenty Questions
          td binary search
        tr.fragment
          td Ulam's game
          td error-correcting codes
        tr.fragment
          td IMO 2012 P3
          td list decoding with no long run of errors
  section
    h3 Closing
    p Ordinary Twenty Questions is binary search.
    p.fragment Ulam's game is error-correcting codes.
    p.fragment IMO 2012 P3 is list decoding with a special rule:
    p.fragment errors are allowed, but not $k+1$ in a row.
    p.fragment.red The threshold $2^k$ comes from the $k$ bits Bob can use after forcing one suspicious answer.
